"/1smDc1j5_1DZePYdC08cXBOZUNEvff5G8YECh-"
"k_MiEI/edit?gid=260896449#gid=260896449>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:95
msgid ""
"You will soon discover which particular examples resonate with other "
"people. Be prepared to be be surprised -- the ones that seem most "
"impressive to *you* won't always be the ones that others get excited "
"about."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:97
msgid ""
"It takes a while to get good at thinking like this. Do it early and do it"
" often. If the first time you do it is in an actual interview situation, "
"that's much too late."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:101
msgid "Bad interview advice"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:103
msgid ""
"Let's get some bad advice out of the way. Bad advice is not given in "
"order to cause harm. It's well-intentioned, and it represents natural "
"anxieties, inclinations and even values, which is what makes it so "
"problematic - we often see bad advice and think: *yes, that makes sense*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:107
msgid "Being yourself"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:109
msgid ""
"You will read, over and over again, that you should \"just be yourself in"
" the interview\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:111
msgid ""
"Don't fall for this. This advice encourages you to take a passive "
"approach, trusting that things will work out because you are the right "
"kind of person."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:115
msgid "Performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:117
msgid ""
"The preparation you do is for your performance in your interview. That's "
"performance as in \"performance in an examination\" or \"performance on "
"the sports field\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:119
msgid ""
"Would you go into an examination or a tough competition \"just being "
"yourself?\" Presumably not. The people who do that don't do very well. "
"The ones who do well are the ones who have prepared for that moment, so "
"that when it comes, they are ready to be the version of themselves that "
"can succeed in the exam or the competition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:121
msgid ""
"It's the same in a job interview. The ones who do well are the ones who "
"have prepared, so that in the hour of the interview they can step out of "
"where they are now, to where they are going to be."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:123
msgid ""
"To perform well in an interview is not to deliver a well-rehearsed "
"speech. It's to have thought about and thought through the challenge, "
"imagining its possibilities and the responses you would offer in return, "
"and to think about what that will demonstrate to your interviewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:125
msgid ""
"Performance is not who we *are*, but what we *do*. It's separate from us,"
" and can be measured, or at least assessed and judged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:127
msgid ""
"Don't settle for \"just\" doing or being anything anything. Think about "
"your performance, and what the interviewer will have to see and measure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:131
msgid "Selling yourself"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:133
msgid ""
"\"How do I sell myself in a job interview?\" is a common question. And "
"you will find hundreds of articles on how to sell yourself:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:135
msgid ""
"Like a marketer or salesperson, your focus is on promoting yourself as "
"the product the hiring manager should buy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:137
msgid "or:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:139
msgid ""
"To better sell yourself, in a job interview, become a salesperson. What "
"you are selling is yourself - you are the product."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:141
msgid ""
"This is actually atrocious advice. It's a terrible way to think about "
"approaching an interview. You are not a *thing*. **Do not try to sell "
"yourself.** Put this idea right out of your mind."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:143
msgid ""
"It is a very peculiar experience when a candidate starts to do this. They"
" will judge a certain moment in the conversation to be the right one for "
"their sales pitch, take a breath, and dive into it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:145
msgid "You can find advice *literally* to say things like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:147
msgid ""
"My drive to succeed succeed and my ability to learn quickly, combined "
"with my proactive attitude, make me confident Iâ€™ll be able to tackle the "
"challenges of this role."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:149
msgid ""
"This is a completely weird thing for a human being to say. It's "
"irritating, even embarrassing for the interviewer. **Nobody wants to hear"
" you selling yourself.** Your interviewers will not welcome your "
"\"elevator pitch\", nor you \"impactful closing statement\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:153
msgid "What's in common?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:155
msgid ""
"What's wrong with both these examples of bad advice is that they imagine "
"the candidate as some kind of *thing*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:157
msgid ""
"**You are not a sample of goods being measured, weighed or inspected, or "
"sold.** You are a person, and in the interview you need to be the person "
"you are going to be, in the future, *in that particular job*, and that is"
" how you need to think about yourself, during the interview and during "
"your preparation for it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-performance.rst:159
msgid ""
"And this is probably the single most significant thing that a candidate "
"can do to ensure success: not to go in with the hope that what you put on"
" the table will be be attractive, and to be concerned with that, but to "
"**go in as a participant**, with a shared responsibility for making this "
"a successful encounter."
msgstr ""

